                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d689">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">493.11/1637: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1"
                            type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-06-03T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >June 3, 1932—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 3—5:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>601. Legation’s 570, May 27, noon. Following from American Consul General at
                    Nanking.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“June 2, 4 p.m. In conversation June 1, 5 p.m., Vice Minister <persName
                            corresp="frus1932v03#p_HM1">Hsu Mo</persName> said that the Ministry was
                        anxious to receive a reply from the Department indicating whether the
                        postponement of the indemnity <pb facs="0716" n="618" xml:id="pg_618"/>
                        could now be considered settled and in this connection he referred to the
                        views expressed to me in previous interviews (see my telegram May 25, 6
                        p.m.).”</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
